:INFO
The Most Ambitious American Novel I Have Read
Invisible Man follows a nameless Black narrator from the American South to Harlem \
in the 1930s and 1940s, and documents the systematic ways in which white America \
refuses to see him as an individual. Ralph Ellison spent seven years writing the \
novel and the ambition of it is visible on every page: the prose is dense and \
allusive, the structure is deliberately fragmented, and the arguments inside \
it are still the most sophisticated I have encountered in American fiction about \
identity and what it means to be seen.

